{"id":14881387,"mediaExerciseId":"0451618a-df4a-4755-8c36-12a7fcedc0b0","exerciseName":"8","chapterName":"13","chapterTitle":"Return, Risk, and The Security Market Line","groupId":null,"groupTitle":null,"isPremium":true,"sectionName":"13.8","sectionTitle":"The SML and the Cost of Capital: A Preview","pageNumber":447,"solutions":[{"id":5982077,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this exercise, we are asked to assess the security market line and the cost of capital. \n\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/04/8c70642f44b97ac48555d776a85441ed/c3adf296f3f4c679b9919bcd143a882f/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/04/8c70642f44b97ac48555d776a85441ed/c3adf296f3f4c679b9919bcd143a882f/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"The **security market line** is a positive slope line that shows the correlation between a security's expected return and volatility.\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":68,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/04/8c70642f44b97ac48555d776a85441ed/84b12ada013bdb06420655f4f50a8950/lateximg_large.png","width":1004},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/04/8c70642f44b97ac48555d776a85441ed/84b12ada013bdb06420655f4f50a8950/lateximg.png","width":503}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"## 8a. \n\nA positive net present value investment would plot above the security market line. This is due to the fact that its expected return is higher than that which is available in stock markets for the same risks. The internal rate of return of the investment's net present value is higher than the required rate of return.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"